tford, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Whitford, Devon, England":"Whitford, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Biset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: short form of   Robinet  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Binette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Cecile, Normand, Raoul, Alain, Alphe, Donat, Fernand, Francois, Gedeon, Gilles.","Altered form of French   Binet  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>.","History: René Binet from Saint-Jean-de-Sauves in Vienne, France, married Catherine Bourgeois in Quebec City, QC, in 1667."]},{"name":"Robinet","meanings":["French: from a pet form of the personal name   Robin  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Biset was born in 1200, in England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Biset, was 15 and her mother, Alice Basset, was 20. She married William d'Auberville in 1225, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1285, in Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1200–1285":"1200–1285","1218–1256":"1218–1256","1226–1276":"1226–1276","1237–1278":"1237–1278","1196–1248":"1196–1248","1225–1280":"1225–1280","1185–1241":"1185–1241","1180–1224":"1180–1224","before 24 August 1241":"enne 24. augustit 1241","18 February 1248":"18. veebruar 1248","1285":"1285","1241":"1241","1185":"1185","1196":"1196","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","30 October 1280":"30. oktoober 1280","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1256":"1256","1200":"1200","1276":"1276","1218":"1218","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Preston